Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` and use the `Shell.Current.Navigation` to handle both hardware/software back:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Fire-and-forget the async prompt
        Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        });

        return true; // cancel the default navigation
    }
}
```

> `return true` suppresses the default back behavior. The dialog then decides whether to navigate.

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button:**

In your XAML, hide the default back button and add your own toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>
</ContentPage>
```

Or set it inline:

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                        Command="{Binding CancelCommand}"
                        IconOverride="" />
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

Wire up `CancelCommand` to the same confirmation logic:

```csharp
public ICommand CancelCommand { get; }

public EditProductPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();

    CancelCommand = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            return;
        }

        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });

    BindingContext = this;
}
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles Android hardware/gesture back; `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the Shell toolbar button — you need both.
- `TextOverride="Cancel"` replaces the default back arrow with text.
- Set `IconOverride=""` (empty string) to remove the arrow icon on platforms that show both.
